nds Lion), one of the country’s highest honours. Since its foundation in 1995, Corneille had been an active and encouraging supporter of the CoBrA Museum in Amstelveen, just south of Amsterdam. Works by Corneille can be seen at Centre Georges Pompidou, Paris. Corneille married Natacha and had one son. He died in Auvers-sur-Oise, France, on 5 September 2010. As an advocate for pushing beyond rules, Corneille remains an important figure in thehistory of modern Dutch art.','Italy','Domingo','Milella',1981,-1,1,'',1),(149,'Belgium-born Dutch artist. Guillaume Cornelis Beverloo, or Corneille (‘crow’) as he is known, was born to Dutch parents in Liège, Belgium, in 1922. His family moved to The Netherlands when he was 12.He studied at the Academy of Art in Amsterdam, but this didn’t last long as Corneille found the teaching too conservative; he preferred to gain inspiration from artists such as Joan Miró and Paul Klee. \n\nHis debut solo exhibition was held in the Dutch northern city of Groningen in 1946, followed a year later by a joint exhibition with his friend Karel Appel, in Amsterdam. But it was in Paris in November 1948 when Corneille and five other artists left a conference on surrealism in protest at its ‘sterile theory’ and ‘dogmatism’, that brought him and fellow artists to the attention of the contemporary art world. The result was the formation of CoBrA, after the initials of Copenhagen, Brussels and Amsterdam, the home cities of its founders: Asger Jorn, Joseph Noiret, Christian Dotremont, Constant Nieuwenhuys, Karel Appel and Corneille. These men believed in regaining a spontaneity and freedom of expression in their art, and to embrace the experimental once more. The group’s first exhibition, held in 1949 at Stedelijk Museum, Amsterdam,drew contentious criticism. The second and final CoBrA exhibiton, held in 1951 in Liège’s Palais des Beaux-Arts,featured works by its now 17 members. Corneille also contributed poems to several of the ten editions of CoBrA mag