Noiret, Christian Dotremont, Constant Nieuwenhuys, Karel Appel and Corneille. These men believed in regaining a spontaneity and freedom of expression in their art, and to embrace the experimental once more. The group’s first exhibition, held in 1949 at Stedelijk Museum, Amsterdam,drew contentious criticism. The second and final CoBrA exhibiton, held in 1951 in Liège’s Palais des Beaux-Arts,featured works by its now 17 members. Corneille also contributed poems to several of the ten editions of CoBrA magazine. Citing internal disagreements the group disbanded in that year, but many of its members remained friends.\n\nCorneille had moved to Paris in 1950, which became his base for the next 60 years. During the 1950s and 1960s Corneille travelled extensively, collecting art and sculpture from Africa. The influence of this, together with his use of a table top as a horizontal rather than vertical ‘easel’, caused a shift in Corneille’s output. Rather than muted colours used in semi-abstraction, themes of animals in nature or nudes were used with bright colours. The scale enlargened too. \n\nCorneille was also a keen and highly accomplished printmaker. A collection of his lithographs, For Jorn (1975-6), is held in the Tate collection, London. In 1997 he was made a commander in the Orde van de Nederlandse Leeuw (Order of the Netherlands Lion), one of the country’s highest honours. Since its foundation in 1995, Corneille had been an active and encouraging supporter of the CoBrA Museum in Amstelveen, just south of Amsterdam. Works by Corneille can be seen at Centre Georges Pompidou, Paris. Corneille married Natacha and had one son. He died in Auvers-sur-Oise, France, on 5 September 2010. As an advocate for pushing beyond rules, Corneille remains an important figure in thehistory of modern Dutch art.','','Unknown','',-1,-1,1,'',1),(153,'Belgium-born Dutch artist. Guillaume Cornelis Beverloo, or Corneille (‘crow’) as he is known, was born to Dutch parents in Liège, Belgium, in 