er, book illustrator or writer, are marked by a strong sense of reality with a particular empathy for the environment and lives of the fishing population. Much of his oeuvre was inspired by his elder compatriot Albert Engström, also a painter, illustrator and writer. \n\nSvensson’s first exhibition was as a part of a group exhibition at Röda Kvarn in Stockholm in 1937. His first solo show (which became his breakthrough as an artist) was at Galerie Moderne in Stockholm in 1940. He continued to have solo exhibitions in the city, of note being those in 1943, 1947 and 1955.\n\nHis fascination for islands and islets didn’t only rest with the Swedish archipelago. Between the years 1947-58 he made several trips to Scotland’s Orkney, Shetland and Faroe islands. In 1963 he set out for the remote South Atlantic island of Tristan da Cunha on board the M/V Bornholm which was returning evacuees from the island’s 1961 volcanic eruption. For this island he created four sets of stamps (1972-86) marking the passage of time from longboats to the modern new harbour. His initial set was the first not to include the face or silhouette of Queen Elizabeth.\nIn 1978 he received an honorary doctorate from the University of Stockholm. Svensson’s works are represented at the Swedish National Museum and Waldemarsudde in Stockholm, as well as in other Swedish museums.','','Unknown artist','',-1,-1,1,'',1),(166,'Swedish painter. Born in Stockholm in 1910, Roland Svensson studied at the city’s Royal Academy of Fine Art, but later, in 1936, in London and France. During his 60-year artistic career, he became a foremost portrayer of the outer islands and islets of the Stockholm archipelago. His studio was on the island Möja. His works, whether as a black-and-white artist, painter, book illustrator or writer, are marked by a strong sense of reality with a particular empathy for the environment and lives of the fishing population. Much of his oeuvre was inspired by his elder compatriot Albert Engström, also a painter, illustrator and writer. \n\nSvensson’s first exhibition was as a part of a group exhibition at Röda Kvarn in Stockholm in 1937. His first solo show (which became his breakthrough as an artist) was at Galerie Moderne in Stockholm in 1940. He continued to have solo exhibitions in the city, of note being those in 1943, 1947 and 1955.\n\nHis fascination for islands and islets didn’t only rest with the Swedish archipelago. Between the years 1947-58 he made several trips to Scotland’s Orkney, Shetland and Faroe islands. In 1963 he set out for the remote South Atlantic island of Tristan da Cunha on board the M/V Bornholm which was returning evacuees from the island’s 1961 volcanic eruption. For this island he created four sets of stamps (1972-86) marking the passage of time from longboats to the modern new harbour. His initial set was the first not to include the face or silhouette of Queen Elizabeth.\nIn 1978 he received an honorary doctorate from the University of Stockholm. Svensson’s works are represented at the Swedish National Museum and Waldemarsudde in Stockholm, as well as in other Swedish museums.','Sweden','Lenea','Artertig',-1,-1,1,'',1),(167,'Swedish painter. Born in Stockholm in 1910, Roland Svensson studied at the city’s Royal Academy of Fine Art, but later, in 1936, in London and France. During his 60-year artistic career, he became a foremost portrayer of the outer islands and islets of the Stockholm archipelago. His studio was on the island Möja. His works, whether as a black-and-white artist, painter, book illustrator or writer, are marked by a strong sense of reality with a particular empathy for the environment and lives of the fishing population. Much of his oeuvre was inspired by his elder compatriot Albert Engström, also a painter, illustrator and writer. \n\nSvensson’s first exhibition was as a part of a group exhibition at Röda Kvarn in Stockholm in 1937. His first solo show (which became his breakthrough as an artist) was at Galerie Moderne in Stockholm in 1940. He continued to have solo exhibitions in the city, of note being those in 1943, 1947 and 1955.\n\nHis fascination for islands and islets didn’t only rest with the Swedish archipelago. Between the years 1947-58 he made several trips to Scotland’s Orkney, Shetland and Faroe islands. In 1963 he set out for the remote South Atlantic island of Tristan da Cunha on board the M/V Bornholm which was returning evacuees from the island’s 1961 volcanic eruption. For this island he created four sets of stamps (1972-86) marking the passage of time from longboats to the modern new harbour. His initial set was the first not to include the face or silhouette of Queen Elizabeth.\nIn 1978 he received an honorary doctorate from the University of Stockholm. Svensson’s works are represented at the Swedish National Museum and Waldemarsudde in Stockholm, as well as in other Swedish museums.','Sweden','John','Bauer',1882,1918,1,'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Bauer_(illustrator)',1),(168,'Swedish painter. Born in Stockholm in 1910, Roland Svensson studied at the city’s Royal Academy of Fine Art, but later, in 1936, in London and France. During his 60-year artistic career, he became a foremost portrayer of the outer islands and islets of the Stockholm archipelago. His studio was on the island Möja. His works, whether as a black-and-white artist, painter, book illustrator or writer, are marked by a strong sense of reality with a particular empathy for the environment and lives of the fishing population. Much of his oeuvre was inspired by his elder compatriot Albert Engström, also a painter, illustrator and writer. \n\nSvensson’s first exhibition was as a part of a group exhibition at Röda Kvarn in Stockholm in 1937. His first solo show (which became his breakthrough as an artist) was at Galerie Moderne in Stockholm in 1940. He continued to have solo exhibitions in the city, of note being those in 1943, 1947 and 1955.\n\nHis fascination for islands and islets didn’t only rest with the Swedish archipelago. Between the years 1947-58 he made several trips to Scotland’s Orkney, Shetland and Faroe islands. In 1963 he set out for the remote South Atlantic island of Tristan da Cunha on board the M/V Bornholm which was returning evacuees from the island’s 1961 volcanic eruption. For this island he created four sets of stamps (1972-86) marking the passage of time from longboats to the modern new harbour. His initial set was the first not to include the face or silhouette of Queen Elizabeth.\nIn 1978 he received an honorary doctorate from the University of Stockholm. Svensson’s works are represented at the Swedish National Museum and Waldemarsudde in Stockholm, as well as in other Swedish museums.','France','Marc','Ricourt',1965,-1,1,'',1),(169,'English painter and draughtsman.John Constable, often associated with his contemporary compatriot J.M.W. Turner, is one of the most important British landscape painters of the early 19th century. Known as a great naturalist, Constable preferred to paint the places he knew well and as such started out as an amateur with depictions of the Suffolk countryside near the River Stour. He was born the second son of Golding Constable, a miller, merchant and gentleman farmer at East Bergholt, Suffolk. By 1799 he was studying at the Royal Academy Schools training, as was the custom, as a history rather than landscape painter. Returning to Bergholt in 1802, Constable was determined to represent nature via local country scenes with the strong belief that there was ‘room enough for natural peinture’. The results were stunning oil studies of Stour Valley landscapes such as Dedham Vale, Evening (1802; London, V&A). This was the year he first exhibited at the Royal Academy. \n\nConstable is known to have stayed in Epsom with his uncle James Gubbins in 1806 producing en plein-air oil sketches of the Common and surrounding countryside in August. Immediately after this he visited the Lake District, an area that deeply impressed him and lead to a multitude of graphite and watercolour mountain studies, but only a few depicted in oil. Constable stayed in Epsom again in the summer of 1809 and other known oil sketches date from that visit (e.g. View atEpsom, 1809, London, Tate). By 1810 Constable’s commitment to his native surroundings revealed an adventurous use of colour, an admired variety of brushstroke and detail of individual motifs within a scene. His style reached its maturity in 1821 with his use of colour washed over a graphite underdrawing. As can be seen in Pond and Cottages: A Storm Approaching (1821; London, British Museum) chiaroscuro ¬¬– the distribution of light and dark masses in a picture – was becoming the formative basis of his art. From 1814 Constable insisted on painting oils for exhibition directly from nature, usually into a sketchbook (1814; London, V&A). He only discarded this methodwhen his canvasses stretched to 1.8 metres for the canal scenes of 1821-2. By the 1830s Constable was creating extraordinary, expressionistic oils, using his now preferred palette knife, as well as slashes, slabs and dribbles of often pure colour.','England','John','Constable',1776,1837,1,'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Constable',1),(170,'Portuguese-born French painter. Having arrived in Paris from Lisbon in 1928, a talented Marie-Hélène Vieira da Silva studieda diverse range of art: initially it was sculpture with Emile-Antoine Bourdelle and then with Charles Despiau; the following year she began engraving in Stanley William Hayter’s Atelier 17, before designing carpets for Dolly Chareau’s Art Deco interiors. The work of Joaquín Torres García (1874-1949), Uruguayan artist and theorist who was also living in Paris at this time, became an influence. He formed part of a future group Cercle et Carré (Circle and Square), promoter of the first exhibition of Constructivist and abstract art in Paris in 1930. This was the year Vieira da Silva married Hungarian artist Árpád Szènes. \n\nBy 1933 Vieira da Silva had exhibited in the highly respected Galerie Jeanne Bucher and in 1937 she had a second show there where her distinctive style using the diamonds and squares of Portuguese azulejos (tin-glazed ceramic tilework) combined with allusions to chessboards and card gamesbegan to come to the fore (e.g.Chess Game, 1943; Paris, Pompidou). \n\nVieiradaSilva’s subject matter became more strongly political prior to and during World War II as is evident in works such as Flags (1939; Düsseldorf, Kstsamml. Nordrhein-Westfalen), Disaster (War) (1941-2) and Liberation of Paris (1945). She and Szènes fled first to Portugal, then to Rio de Janeiro, where the couple mixed with the Brazilian intelligentsia. On their return to Paris, VieiradaSilva continued toexhibit at the Galerie Jeanne Bucher, displaying her grey palette yet citing the more colourful landscape Impressionists Jean Bazaine and Alfred Manessier, as well as the structural designs of Gustave Eiffel, as influences. \n\nThe Árpád Szènes-Vieira da Silva Foundation in Lisbon, inaugurated in 1994, houses a museum that features both artists’ works.','Portugal','M. H. Vieira','da Silva',1908,1992,1,'',1),(171,'Swedish painter. Petter Zennström was born in Stockholm but lives and works in Västerljung. He was educated at the Kungliga Konsthögskolan, Stockholm, from 1971 until 1976. During the 1970s Zennström became known for his black-and-white wood engravings. The work was angry and aggressive; words and images combined in order to channel anger at the world’s political, economic and social injustices. The artist once said, ‘I live in the belly of the beast, in the midst of welfare’, and his early art aired his fury with unjustly distributed resources and political violations.\n\nZennström’s oeuvre challenges the opinions and norms of contemporary social society. The works combine figuration with bold abstraction and elements of Pop Art so prevalent in America during the 1960s. His art took a new direction in the 1980s with the use of intense colour combinations leading to a greater degree of abstraction. One of the works from this period, The Secret (1981), was acquired by the Moderna Museet, Stockholm. \n\nDuring the 1980s and the 1990s Zennström developed his painting and his distinctive and unique imagery. Strong colours and organic forms expanded over the surface of the image and the paintings moved from the figurative to the abstract. The paintings no longer commented on a specific political or ideological conflict, but rather related to them. Hidden in the painting, on an implicit level, there is an examination of contemporary life, which is at times difficult to come to terms with. With time, the form of the painting has come to dominate over the explicit message and there is a desire for beauty in colour and shapes. In later works, the paintings have their origin in one of two fundamental forms: the upside down and the mirrored image. The colours are no longer the earlier, bright primary colours but rather a more dull range of brown shades.\n\nZennström’s work reveals, concerns and upsets. His motifs show an artist with a strong and sincere commitment against social, political and economic injustice. The work creeps under the skin of the viewer thanks to the tense mood and the black humour. More recently, the direct political and ideological references have given way to a more implicit agenda and a stronger abstract imagery. The works do, nonetheless, still hold references to a world order that is rarely pleasant, but important, both emotionally and intellectually. \n\nZennström has exhibited widely in both Sweden and abroad. He is represented in Sweden at, among others, Moderna Museet, Stockholm, the National Museum, Stockholm, Borås Konstmuseum, Göteborgs Konstmuseum, Moderna Museet, Malmö, Norrköpings Museum, Samtidsmuseet i Oslo, Sundsvalls Museum and the Kalmar Konstmuseum.','Australia','Margaret','Boko',-1,-1,1,'',1),(172,'Swedish painter. Born in Stockholm in 1910, Roland Svensson studied at the city’s Royal Academy of Fine Art, but later, in 1936, in London and France. During his 60-year artistic career, he became a foremost portrayer of the outer islands and islets of the Stockholm archipelago. His studio was on the island Möja. His works, whether as a black-and-white artist, painter, book illustrator or writer, are marked by a strong sense of reality with a particular empathy for the environment and lives of the fishing population. Much of his oeuvre was inspired by his elder compatriot Albert Engström, also a painter, illustrator and writer. \n\nSvensson’s first exhibition was as a part of a group exhibition at Röda Kvarn in Stockholm in 1937. His first solo show (which became his breakthrough as an artist) was at Galerie Moderne in Stockholm in 1940. He continued to have solo exhibitions in the city, of note being those in 1943, 1947 and 1955.\n\nHis fascination for islands and islets didn’t only rest with the Swedish archipelago. Between the years 1947-58 he made several trips to Scotland’s Orkney, Shetland and Faroe islands. In 1963 he set out for the remote South Atlantic island of Tristan da Cunha on board the M/V Bornholm which was returning evacuees from the island’s 1961 volcanic eruption. For this island he created four sets of stamps (1972-86) marking the passage of time from longboats to the modern new harbour. His initial set was the first not to include the face or silhouette of Queen Elizabeth.\nIn 1978 he received an honorary doctorate from the University of Stockholm. Svensson’s works are represented at the Swedish National Museum and Waldemarsudde in Stockholm, as well as in other Swedish museums.','Sweden','Carl Olof','Larsson',1853,1919,1,'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Larsson',1),(173,'','','','',-1,-1,-1,'',1);
