Museum, Samtidsmuseet i Oslo, Sundsvalls Museum and the Kalmar Konstmuseum.','Expansion',1516,'1516','Signed lower left','21st Century',10400,'Oil on board','Painted in London, UK','60015','Edition 28/70',-1,20200,-1,189,98,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave the UK','','Mat staining, pale stains in margins, minor defects alongside edges of sheet.',NULL,143,1,256,1,1),(257,'Swedish mixed-media artist. Nisse Zetterberg was born in Stockholm, 1910, into an artistic family: his father was a painter (Albert Zetterberg, 1883-1955), and his brother, born a year earlier, became an architect (Olle Zetterberg). Initially he learnt painting with his father, then studied at the College of Art, Stockholm (1929-34), under the varied tutelage of artist, writer and cartoonist Albert Engström, painter and printmaker Olle Hjortzberg and modernist painter Birger Simonsson. This paid off: Zetterberg worked primarily in painting and printmaking, but also in sculpture and decorative work, taking note of the current practices used in countries that he visited, including France, Holland, Belgium and England. \nZetterberg is perhaps most famous for his mixed-media work at Rinkeby subway station, Stockholm, which opened in 1975 and was supplemented in 1985. Capitalising on the runestone-rich area surrounding Stockholm, Zetterberg created, within rust-red rock walls, glistening gold mosaics of local finds excavated from Viking times. The other two artists involved in the station’s decor were Sven Sahlberg, whose large sun of gold with petals of oars hangs from the ceiling, and Lennart Grams, whose paintings of birds flying in the direction of the trains, adorn the track wall. \n\nOther public artworks by Zetterberg are included in Malmö City Library, a bank in Köping, the chancel windows in Torsåkers Church near Uppsala (1965) and a decorative frieze in Åvaskolan, Täby (1973).','The First Empire',1517,'1517','Signed lower left','20th Century',4800,'Mixed media montage','Painted in Florence, Italy','60036','Edition 2/70',-1,4000,-1,189,98,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave the US','','Mat staining, pale stains in margins, minor defects alongside edges of sheet.',NULL,144,1,257,1,1),(258,'Swedish painter, etcher and sculptor. Anders Zorn was brought up by his grandparents at Mora. As he displayed a precocious talent for drawing he was admitted to the preparatory class of the Kungliga Akademien för de Fria Konsterna, Stockholm, at the age of 15. Dissatisfied with the outdated teaching and discipline of the Academy and encouraged by his early success as a painter of watercolour portraits and genre scenes (e.g. Old Woman from Mora, 1879; Zorn Museum, Mora), Zorn left the Academy in 1881 to try to establish an international career. He later resided mainly in London but also travelled extensively in Italy, France, Spain, Algeria and the Balkans and visited Constantinople. However, he continued to spend most of his summers in Sweden.\n\nSommarnöje was paintedat Dalarö in the archipelago outside Stockholm. This had been a very popular and picturesque summer residence since the end of the 19thcentury. Dalarö was an important place for Anders and Emma Zorn, Emma’s family rented a house here during the summer months from the coastal pilot Carl Gustav Dahlström – the man depicted in the boat. Emma and Anders married in 1885 and went to Dalarö at the beginning of the summer of 1886. Zorn found his inspiration and motifs in the surrounding environment and created several of his masterpieces here including Sommarnöje.','Figure',1518,'1518','Signed ‘GAN’ and dated ‘28. Signed ‘Gösta Adrian-Nilsson’ verso','19th Century',5400,'Watercolor on paper','Painted in Venice, Italy','60037','Edition 4/120',-1,7500,-1,80,92,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave France','','',NULL,145,1,258,1,1),(259,'During 1887-8 Zorn turned to oil painting, settling in Paris, where he remained until 1896. Here he began to gain international recognition thanks partly to his portraits and partly to his pictures of nudes (Une Première, 1888; Stockholm, National Museum, and Out of Doors, 1888; Göteborg, Konstmuseum). Zorn adopted the innovative practice of painting nudes en plein air. The virtuoso technique that he had developed in his watercolours was to some extent carried over to his oil paintings, where the broad, free handling of the brush illustrates his admiration for Edouard Manet. During the 1890s his work displayed an increasingly strong feeling for the body’s plasticity, reminiscent of Auguste Renoir. However Zorn, like Sargent and his good friend Max Liebermann (whose portrait Zorn painted in 1891; Zorn Museum, Mora), belonged to the moderate Modernist phalanx who adopted features not only from Impressionism and Japonisme but also from the fashionable art of the Salon. Zorn was also inspired by the Old Masters that he studied in the Louvre, particularly Titian, Velázquez and Rembrandt.','Colour Motion',1519,'1519','Signed ‘GAN’ and dated ‘28. Signed ‘Gösta Adrian-Nilsson’ verso','19th Century',2400,'Watercolor on paper','Painted Brive-la-Gaillarde, France','60038','Edition 22/130',-1,3600,-1,81,70,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave the Germany','','',NULL,145,1,259,1,1),(260,'It was primarily his skill as a portrait painter that gained Zorn international acclaim. His incisive ability to depict the individual character of his model is, for example, apparent in portraits of prominent cultural personalities such as Antonin Proust (1888, private collection) and Coquelin Cadet (1889, Nationalmuseum Stockholm). The model’s surroundings were important; Zorn believed that a portrait should be painted in an environment that was natural for the model. An artificial studio environment was not to his taste. The international esteem Zorn received was not based solely on his paintings but on his exquisite etchings as well. He had worked with this technique since 1882 and produced 289 etchings, a number of which are very well known, among them the portrait of Ernest Renan (1892), Auguste Rodin (1906) and the current example of August Strindberg. Zorn admired and collected the etched works of Rembrandt and considered him to be his artistic forefather in this particular medium.','Fotbollsspelar (Footballers)',1520,'1520','Signed ‘GAN’ and dated ‘28. Signed ‘Gösta Adrian-Nilsson’ verso','20th Century',2900,'Etching','Painted in Turin, Italy','60039','Edition 22/130',-1,1900,-1,81,70,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave the Italy','','',NULL,145,1,260,1,1),(261,'Swedish painter. Thomas Zornat was educated at the Konsthögskolan Valand, Nordiska Konstskolan (The Nordic Art School), Kokkola, Finland and Bild & Form Lunnevad, Linköping, Sweden. He paints strikingly direct monochrome paintings, often painted from photographs, which lead us to an encounter with nature at the edge of civilisation, or confront us with urban dwellings or dwellers.Zornat has shown at Galleri Sander, Norrköping, Galleri Argo, Stockholm and Göteborgs Konstmuseum. He lives and works in Gothenburg, with his wife,Rebecca Burkhalter, who is also an artist.','Le Vase',1521,'1521','Signed ‘GAN’ and dated ‘28. Signed ‘Gösta Adrian-Nilsson’ verso','21st Century',6300,'Oil on panel','Painted in San Felice Circeo, Italy','60040','Edition 21/129',-1,4000,-1,81,70,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave the UK','','',NULL,146,1,261,1,1),(262,'Belgium-born Dutch artist. Guillaume Cornelis Beverloo, or Corneille (‘crow’) as he is known, was born to Dutch parents in Liège, Belgium, in 1922. His family moved to The Netherlands when he was 12.He studied at the Academy of Art in Amsterdam, but this didn’t last long as Corneille found the teaching too conservative; he preferred to gain inspiration from artists such as Joan Miró and Paul Klee. \n\nHis debut solo exhibition was held in the Dutch northern city of Groningen in 1946, followed a year later by a joint exhibition with his friend Karel Appel, in Amsterdam. But it was in Paris in November 1948 when Corneille and five other artists left a conference on surrealism in protest at its ‘sterile theory’ and ‘dogmatism’, that brought him and fellow artists to the attention of the contemporary art world. The result was the formation of CoBrA, after the initials of Copenhagen, Brussels and Amsterdam, the home cities of its founders: Asger Jorn, Joseph Noiret, Christian Dotremont, Constant Nieuwenhuys, Karel Appel and Corneille. These men believed in regaining a spontaneity and freedom of expression in their art, and to embrace the experimental once more. The group’s first exhibition, held in 1949 at Stedelijk Museum, Amsterdam,drew contentious criticism. The second and final CoBrA exhibiton, held in 1951 in Liège’s Palais des Beaux-Arts,featured works by its now 17 members. Corneille also contributed poems to several of the ten editions of CoBrA magazine. Citing internal disagreements the group disbanded in that year, but many of its members remained friends.\n\nCorneille had moved to Paris in 1950, which became his base for the next 60 years. During the 1950s and 1960s Corneille travelled extensively, collecting art and sculpture from Africa. The influence of this, together with his use of a table top as a horizontal rather than vertical ‘easel’, caused a shift in Corneille’s output. Rather than muted colours used in semi-abstraction, themes of animals in nature or nudes were used with bright colours. The scale enlargened too. \n\nCorneille was also a keen and highly accomplished printmaker. A collection of his lithographs, For Jorn (1975-6), is held in the Tate collection, London. In 1997 he was made a commander in the Orde van de Nederlandse Leeuw (Order of the Netherlands Lion), one of the country’s highest honours. Since its foundation in 1995, Corneille had been an active and encouraging supporter of the CoBrA Museum in Amstelveen, just south of Amsterdam. Works by Corneille can be seen at Centre Georges Pompidou, Paris. Corneille married Natacha and had one son. He died in Auvers-sur-Oise, France, on 5 September 2010. As an advocate for pushing beyond rules, Corneille remains an important figure in thehistory of modern Dutch art.','Flat Standing Figure',1522,'1522','Signed ‘GAN’ and dated ‘28. Signed ‘Gösta Adrian-Nilsson’ verso','20th Century',9700,'Oil on canvas','Painted in Grez-sur-Loing, France.','60041','Edition 22/130',-1,13000,-1,81,70,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave the US','','Mat staining, pale stains in margins, minor defects alongside edges of sheet.',NULL,147,1,262,1,1),(263,'Belgium-born Dutch artist. Guillaume Cornelis Beverloo, or Corneille (‘crow’) as he is known, was born to Dutch parents in Liège, Belgium, in 1922. His family moved to The Netherlands when he was 12.He studied at the Academy of Art in Amsterdam, but this didn’t last long as Corneille found the teaching too conservative; he preferred to gain inspiration from artists such as Joan Miró and Paul Klee. \n\nHis debut solo exhibition was held in the Dutch northern city of Groningen in 1946, followed a year later by a joint exhibition with his friend Karel Appel, in Amsterdam. But it was in Paris in November 1948 when Corneille and five other artists left a conference on surrealism in protest at its ‘sterile theory’ and ‘dogmatism’, that brought him and fellow artists to the attention of the contemporary art world. The result was the formation of CoBrA, after the initials of Copenhagen, Brussels and Amsterdam, the home cities of its founders: Asger Jorn, Joseph Noiret, Christian Dotremont, Constant Nieuwenhuys, Karel Appel and Corneille. These men believed in regaining a spontaneity and freedom of expression in their art, and to embrace the experimental once more. The group’s first exhibition, held in 1949 at Stedelijk Museum, Amsterdam,drew contentious criticism. The second and final CoBrA exhibiton, held in 1951 in Liège’s Palais des Beaux-Arts,featured works by its 