become involved with its thriving art scene. Soon Feiler was teaching at the St Ives summer school and, in 1953, he bought and converted a disused chapel in Kerris which became his main home (although he continued to teach in Bristol). \n\nHis first solo show was at the Redfern Gallery, London, in 1953;it was a sell-out. He continued to show at the gallery during the 1950s; in 1954 the Obelisk Gallery in Washington D.C. held the first of several solo exhibitions in America. During the 1950s and 1960s there were many connections between British and American abstract artists: Mark Rothko visited Cornwall in 1958, as is evident in a photograph taken by Feiler featuring Rothko and his wife Mell, together with Heron and Terry Frost, having tea with the Feilersat Kerris. As in Winter Landscape (1950), Feiler’s early gestural landscape oil paintings used thick, earthy colours applied in Expressionistic slabs. As the 1950s progressed, however, his style became more abstract, leaving elements of the landscape dangling in expanses of white, creamy space. It’s often considered that he was ahead of his time as, sadly, this coincided with critical neglect.\n\nExhilarated by coexisting explorations of space in the 1960s, however, Feiler’s accompanying series of more austere geometric abstractions – in which perpendicular and rectangular matrices framed either circular, square or striped inner spaces – formed a turning point. The Redferm Gallery re-engaged with him in 1993, hosting seven shows between 1993 and 2010. The Tate, St Ives, mounted two solo exhibitions (1995 and 2005) and he continued to work in his Cornish studio (which he’d taken over from Wynter in 1975) until his death in 2013.  Feiler’s work is held in public collections worldwide including the Tate, London, the Victoria &Albert Museum, London,the BibliothèqueNationale, Paris, the National Gallery of New Zealand, Wellington and the Gallery of Modern Art, Washington D.C.','Dissonanz',1547,'1547','Signed in white crayon and numbered 22/130, published by ABCD Editions. L./S','20th Century',18300,'Oil on board','Painted in Turin, Italy','60067','Edition 2/70',-1,12200,-1,189,98,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave the US','','Mat staining, pale stains in margins, minor defects alongside edges of sheet.',NULL,163,1,11,1,1),(288,'Anglo-German painter. Paul Feiler became associated with the post-war Modernists in St Ives, Cornwall. Feiler was born in Frankfurt-am-Main in 1918 to a cultured family who nurtured his early interest in art. When the Nazis came to power in 1933, Feiler was sent to school first in Zwolle, The Netherlands, then Canford School in Dorset. By 1936 his parents had joined him in London, his father starting up a dentist practice in Harley Street andFeilerenrolling at the Slade School of Fine Art. Fellow students included Patrick Heron, Bryan Wynter and Kenneth Armitage. At the outbreak of the Second World War, Feiler was interned as an enemy alien in Canada. \n\nWhen he returned to the UK in 1941 he became a teacher at Eastbourne College then at the West of England College of Art in Bristol where, in 1960, he became Head of Painting. His work was first noticed in 1949 as part of the Arts Council’sYoung Contemporaries exhibition in Bristol, and in the following year in the Slade Contemporaries show. 1949 was also the year he first visited Cornwall where it didn’t take long for Heron to convince him to become involved with its thriving art scene. Soon Feiler was teaching at the St Ives summer school and, in 1953, he bought and converted a disused chapel in Kerris which became his main home (although he continued to teach in Bristol). \n\nHis first solo show was at the Redfern Gallery, London, in 1953;it was a sell-out. He continued to show at the gallery during the 1950s; in 1954 the Obelisk Gallery in Washington D.C. held the first of several solo exhibitions in America. During the 1950s and 1960s there were many connections between British and Americ