t was a sell-out. He continued to show at the gallery during the 1950s; in 1954 the Obelisk Gallery in Washington D.C. held the first of several solo exhibitions in America. During the 1950s and 1960s there were many connections between British and American abstract artists: Mark Rothko visited Cornwall in 1958, as is evident in a photograph taken by Feiler featuring Rothko and his wife Mell, together with Heron and Terry Frost, having tea with the Feilersat Kerris. As in Winter Landscape (1950), Feiler’s early gestural landscape oil paintings used thick, earthy colours applied in Expressionistic slabs. As the 1950s progressed, however, his style became more abstract, leaving elements of the landscape dangling in expanses of white, creamy space. It’s often considered that he was ahead of his time as, sadly, this coincided with critical neglect.\n\nExhilarated by coexisting explorations of space in the 1960s, however, Feiler’s accompanying series of more austere geometric abstractions – in which perpendicular and rectangular matrices framed either circular, square or striped inner spaces – formed a turning point. The Redferm Gallery re-engaged with him in 1993, hosting seven shows between 1993 and 2010. The Tate, St Ives, mounted two solo exhibitions (1995 and 2005) and he continued to work in his Cornish studio (which he’d taken over from Wynter in 1975) until his death in 2013.  Feiler’s work is held in public collections worldwide including the Tate, London, the Victoria &Albert Museum, London,the BibliothèqueNationale, Paris, the National Gallery of New Zealand, Wellington and the Gallery of Modern Art, Washington D.C.','The First Empire',1557,'1557','Signed lower right','21st Century',2500,'Beech','Painted in San Felice Circeo, Italy','60071','Edition 26/75',-1,2500,-1,75,65,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave the US','','Mat staining, pale stains in margins, minor defects alongside edges of sheet.',NULL,168,1,21,1,1),(298,'From the late 1950s, Pierre Soulages’sbrushstrokes became looser and more rhythmical, until, by the mid-1960s, broadly brushed shapes extended right across the canvas in a gesture that appears to extend beyond the support. His Painting, dated 5 February 1964 and held at the Muséed’ArtContemporain Montreal, measures 2.35 x 3 metres. Some of these pictures were made using trowels or knives to scrape off parts of the upper layer of paint to reveal the red, yellow or blue underneath.Soulages never named his works, preferring to identify them with their date only.\n\nAlthough the bold, gestural character of Soulages’s work has often been compared to the Abstract Expressionism of such artists as Franz Kline, the resemblance is only superficial. Instead of relying on improvisation, he built up his forms very deliberately to achieve a formal, balanced beauty. His work took a decisive new turn in 1979, when he began to make very large paintings, often combining several panels that were entirely covered with a thick coat of black oil paint. For their effect, they relied on contrasts of texture, rhythm and direction of brushwork, produced by alternating bands of corrugated or smooth surfaces.\n\nSoulages’s output also incorporates aquatints, lithographs and, since 1975, bronzes connected to the irregular shapes of the plates used when creating the aquatints. He is well represented in museums throughout the world, notably in Germany, USA, Canada, Brazil, Japan, Scandinavia, London, Vienna, Jersualem, Rotterdam and Zürich, as well as several in France. In 2005 Soulages and his wife Colette donated 500 works to his native town of Rodez. A museum opening in 2014 is being built to house these works.','Figure',1558,'1558','Signed lower right','20th Century',5000,'ink on paper','Painted in Grez-sur-Loing, France.','60072','Edition 92/150',-1,5000,-1,48,41,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave France','','',NULL,124,1,22,1,1),(299,'English painter and draughtsman.John Constable, often associated with his contemporary compatriot J.M.W. Turner, is one of the most important British landscape painters of the early 19th century. Known as a great naturalist, Constable preferred to paint the places he knew well and as such started out as an amateur with depictions of the Suffolk countryside near the River Stour. He was born the second son of Golding Constable, a miller, merchant and gentleman farmer at East Bergholt, Suffolk. By 1799 he was studying at the Royal Academy Schools training, as was the custom, as a history rather than landscape painter. Returning to Bergholt in 1802, Constable was determined to represent nature via local country scenes with the strong belief that there was ‘room enough for natural peinture’. The results were stunning oil studies of Stour Valley landscapes such as Dedham Vale, Evening (1802; London, V&A). This was the year he first exhibited at the Royal Academy. \n\nConstable is known to have stayed in Epsom with his uncle James Gubbins in 1806 producing en plein-air oil sketches of the Common and surrounding countryside in August. Immediately after this he visited the Lake District, an area that deeply impressed him and lead to a multitude of graphite and watercolour mountain studies, but only a few depicted in oil. Constable stayed in Epsom again in the summer of 1809 and other known oil sketches date from that visit (e.g. View atEpsom, 1809, London, Tate). By 1810 Constable’s commitment to his native surroundings revealed an adventurous use of colour, an admired variety of brushstroke and detail of individual motifs within a scene. His style reached its maturity in 1821 with his use of colour washed over a graphite underdrawing. As can be seen in Pond and Cottages: A Storm Approaching (1821; London, British Museum) chiaroscuro ¬¬– the distribution of light and dark masses in a picture – was becoming the formative basis of his art. From 1814 Constable insisted on painting oils for exhibition directly from nature, usually into a sketchbook (1814; London, V&A). He only discarded this methodwhen his canvasses stretched to 1.8 metres for the canal scenes of 1821-2. By the 1830s Constable was creating extraordinary, expressionistic oils, using his now preferred palette knife, as well as slashes, slabs and dribbles of often pure colour. \n\nThe oil sketchWalton Church, Epsom has been in Germany since before the First World War, and has not been seen in England since. The Heinemann Gallery, founded in Munich in 1872, was an early supporter of Constable in Germany. The original, thin card support was laid onto a hardwood panel in the late 19th century. The panel was removed by Sarah Cove (Constable Research Project) in 2012 revealing the handwritten inscription ‘Walton Church/Epsom’ and dated by her to 1806.','Colour Motion',1559,'1559','Signed','19th Century',1700,'oil on card','Painted in Toulouse, France','60073','Edition 92/150',-1,1100,-1,65,66,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave the Germany','','Mat staining, pale stains in margins, minor defects alongside edges of sheet.',NULL,169,1,23,1,1),(300,'Portuguese-born French painter. Having arrived in Paris from Lisbon in 1928, a talented Marie-Hélène Vieira da Silva studieda diverse range of art: initially it was sculpture with Emile-Antoine Bourdelle and then with Charles Despiau; the following year she began engraving in Stanley William Hayter’s Atelier 17, before designing carpets for Dolly Chareau’s Art Deco interiors. The work of Joaquín Torres García (1874-1949), Uruguayan artist and theorist who was also living in Paris at this time, became an influence. He formed part of a future group Cercle et Carré (Circle and Square), promoter of the first exhibition of Constructivist and abstract art in Paris in 1930. This was the year Vieira da Silva married Hungarian artist Árpád Szènes. \n\nBy 1933 Vieira da Silva had exhibited in the highly respected Galerie Jeanne Bucher and in 1937 she had a second show there where her distinctive style using the diamonds and squares of Portuguese azulejos (tin-glazed ceramic tilework) combined with allusions to chessboards and card gamesbegan to come to the fore (e.g.Chess Game, 1943; Paris, Pompidou). \n\nVieiradaSilva’s subject matter became more strongly political prior to and during World War II as is evident in works such as Flags (1939; Düsseldorf, Kstsamml. Nordrhein-Westfalen), Disaster (War) (1941-2) and Liberation of Paris (1945). She and Szènes fled first to Portugal, then to Rio de Janeiro, where the couple mixed with the Brazilian intelligentsia. On their return to Paris, VieiradaSilva continued toexhibit at the Galerie Jeanne Bucher, displaying her grey palette yet citing the more colourful landscape Impressionists Jean Bazaine and Alfred Manessier, as well as the structural designs of Gustave Eiffel, as influences. \n\nThis Untitledpiece (circa 1965-70) was painted at a time when Vieira da Silva was at the height of her power: in 1966 she was the first woman to receive the French government’s Grand Prix National des Arts; its creation alsoco-incided with her retrospective at the Musée National d’Art Moderne in Paris (1969-70), which then toured to Rotterdam, Oslo, Basle and Lisbon. She moved in popular cultural circles: she painted a stage curtain for Arthur Adamov’s La Parodie,collaboratedregularly with poet René Char, as well as painting shield-like backdrops for sculptor Germaine Richier’s bronze figures.\n\nThe Árpád Szènes-Vieira da Silva Foundation in Lisbon, inaugurated in 1994, houses a museum that features both artists’ works.','Fotbollsspelar (Footballers)',1560,'1560','Signed in pencil lower right','20th Century',2600,'Oil and pencil on cardboard','Painted in Berlin, Germany','60074','Edition 97/150',-1,2100,-1,156,217,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave the Italy','','Mat staining, pale stains in margins, minor defects alongside edges of sheet.',NULL,170,1,277,1,1),(301,'From the late 1950s, Pierre Soulages’sbrushstrokes became looser and more rhythmical, until, by the mid-1960s, broadly brushed shapes extended right across the canvas in a gesture that appears to extend beyond the support. His Painting, dated 5 February 1964 and held at the Muséed’ArtContemporain Montreal, measures 2.35 x 3 metres. Some of these pictures were made using trowels or knives to scrape off parts of the upper layer of paint to reveal the red, yellow or blue underneath.Soulages never named his works, preferring to identify them with their date only.\n\nAlthough the bold, gestural character of Soulages’s work has often been compared to the Abstract Expressionism of such artists as Franz Kline, the resemblance is only superficial. Instead of relying on improvisation, he built up his forms very deliberately to achieve a formal, balanced beauty. His work took a decisive new turn in 1979, when he began to make very large paintings, often combining several panels that were entirely covered with a thick coat of black oil paint. For their effect, they relied on contrasts of texture, rhythm and direction of brushwork, produced by alternating bands of corrugated or smooth surfaces.\n\nSoulages’s output also incorporates aquatints, lithographs and, since 1975, bronzes connected to the irregular shapes of the plates used when creating the aquatints. He is well represented in museums throughout the world, notably in Germany, USA, Canada, Brazil, Japan, Scandinavia, London, Vienna, Jersualem, Rotterdam and Zürich, as well as several in France. In 2005 Soulages and his wife Colette donated 500 works to his native town of Rodez. A museum opening in 2014 is being built to house these works.','Le Vase',1561,'1561','Signed in white crayon and numbered 22/130, published by ABCD Editions. L./S','21st Century',3400,'Oil on MDF board','Painted in London, UK','60075','Edition 28/70',-1,4400,-1,189,98,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave the UK','','Mat staining, pale stains in margins, minor defects alongside edges of sheet.',NULL,143,1,25,1,1),(302,'English painter and draughtsman.John Constable, often associated with his contemporary compatriot J.M.W. Turner, is one of the most important British landscape painters of the early 19th century. Known as a great naturalist, Constable preferred to paint the places he knew well and as such started out as an amateur with depictions of the Suffolk countryside near the River Stour. He was born the second son of Golding Constable, a miller, merchant and gentleman farmer at East Bergholt, Suffolk. By 1799 he was studying at the Royal Academy Schools training, as was the custom, as a history rather than landscape painter. Returning to Bergholt in 1802, Constable was determined to represent nature via local country scenes with the strong belief that there was ‘room enough for natural peinture’. The results were stunning oil studies of Stour Valley landscapes such as Dedham Vale, Evening (1802; London, V&A). This was the year he first exhibited at the Royal Academy. \n\nConstable is known to have stayed in Epsom with his uncle James Gubbins in 1806 producing en plein-air oil sketches of the Common and surrounding countryside in August. Immediately after this he visited the Lake District, an area that deeply impressed him and lead to a multitude of graphite and watercolour mountain studies, but only a few depicted in oil. Constable stayed in Epsom again in the summer of 1809 and other known oil sketches date from that visit (e.g. View atEpsom, 1809, London, Tate). By 1810 Constable’s commitment to his native surroundings revealed an adventurous use of colour, an admired variety of brushstroke and detail of individual motifs within a scene. His style reached its maturity in 1821 with his use of colour washed over a graphite underdrawing. As can be seen in Pond and Cottages: A Storm Approaching (1821; London, British Museum) chiaroscuro ¬¬– the distribution of light and dark masses in a picture – was becoming the formative basis of his art. From 1814 Constable insisted on painting oils for exhibition directly from nature, usually into a sketchbook (1814; London, V&A). He only discarded this methodwhen his canvasses stretched to 1.8 metres for the canal scenes of 1821-2. By the 1830s Constable was creating extraordinary, expressionistic oils, using his now preferred palette knife, as well as slashes, slabs and dribbles of often pure colour. \n\nThe oil sketchWalton Church, Epsom has been in Germany since before the First World War, and has not been seen in England since. The Heinemann Gallery, founded in Munich in 1872, was an early supporter of Constable in Germany. The original, thin card support was laid onto a hardwood panel in the late 19th century. The panel was removed by Sarah Cove (Constable Research Project) in 2012 revealing the handwritten inscription ‘Walton Church/Epsom’ and dated by her to 1806.','Flat Standing Figure',1562,'1562','Signed in white crayon and numbered 22/130, published by ABCD Editions. L./S','21st Century',3400,'Oil on MDF board','Painted in Florence, Italy','60076','Edition 2/70',-1,4400,-1,189,98,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave the US','','',NULL,143,1,26,1,1),(303,'Portuguese-born French painter. Having arrived in Paris from Lisbon in 1928, a talented Marie-Hélène Vieira da Silva studieda diverse range of art: initially it was sculpture with Emile-Antoine Bourdelle and then with Charles Despiau; the following year she began engraving in Stanley William Hayter’s Atelier 17, before designing carpets for Dolly Chareau’s Art Deco interiors. The work of Joaquín Torres García (1874-1949), Uruguayan artist and theorist who was also living in Paris at this time, became an influence. He formed part of a future group Cercle et Carré (Circle and Square), promoter of the first exhibition of Constructivist and abstract art in Paris in 1930. This was the year Vieira da Silva married Hungarian artist Árpád Szènes. \n\nBy 1933 Vieira da Silva had exhibited in the highly respected Galerie Jeanne Bucher and in 1937 she had a second show there where her distinctive style using the diamonds and squares of Portuguese azulejos (tin-glazed ceramic tilework) combined with allusions to chessboards and card gamesbegan to come to the fore (e.g.Chess Game, 1943; Paris, Pompidou). \n\nVieiradaSilva’s subject matter became more strongly political prior to and during World War II as is evident in works such as Flags (1939; Düsseldorf, Kstsamml. Nordrhein-Westfalen), Disaster (War) (1941-2) and Liberation of Paris (1945). She and Szènes fled first to Portugal, then to Rio de Janeiro, where the couple mixed with the Brazilian intelligentsia. On their return to Paris, VieiradaSilva continued toexhibit at the Galerie Jeanne Bucher, displaying her grey palette yet citing the more colourful landscape Impressionists Jean Bazaine and Alfred Manessier, as well as the structural designs of Gustave Eiffel, as influences. \n\nThis Untitledpiece (circa 1965-70) was painted at a time when Vieira da Silva was at the height of her power: in 1966 she was the first woman to receive the French government’s Grand Prix National des Arts; its creation alsoco-incided with her retrospective at the Musée National d’Art Moderne in Paris (1969-70), which then toured to Rotterdam, Oslo, Basle and Lisbon. She moved in popular cultural circles: she painted a stage curtain for Arthur Adamov’s La Parodie,collaboratedregularly with poet René Char, as well as painting shield-like backdrops for sculptor Germaine Richier’s bronze figures.\n\nThe Árpád Szènes-Vieira da Silva Foundation in Lisbon, inaugurated in 1994, houses a museum that features both artists’ works.','Verticale Brune 1 (Vertical Brown 1)',1563,'1563','Signed in white crayon and numbered 21/130, published by ABCD Editions. L./S.','21st Century',3400,'Oil on MDF board','Painted in Venice, Italy','60077','Edition 4/120',-1,4400,-1,80,92,'This artwork requires an export licence to leave France','','',NULL,143,1,27,